[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Hey guys. So, I think I may have found the best Docker manager that is out there right now. And I know that\'s a pretty bold statement, but I\'ve tested quite a few Docker managers in my home lab already, such as Portainer, Dohand, Koolify, Docky, and while all of them'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'are great, they seem to be built for just one specific use case and miss features many of the other tools have. But Arcane feels different. This is a free and open-source Docker manager that'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'just looks incredibly polished and it has all of the features, trust me guys, all of the features you need in a home lab that you usually miss in the other tools. It has Docker Swarm support like'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Portainer. It can do image builds like Dock Ploy and Coolify. It has update checks and vulnerability scanning like Docand has and even comes with other cool features on top of that such as'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'monitoring, volume backups, notifications, GitHubs, web hooks. And it has honestly one of the nicest Docker network and port overviews that I have seen so far. And I also love the angle'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'behind it because Arcane does not feel like a tool that tries to become an enterprise platform for container orchestration. It feels like someone just looked at the daily Docker tasks we actually try to solve in our home apps'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and then built a really clean and powerful system for that. Now, before we start with that, I also like to talk about another thing that gets messy real quickly when you\'re managing containers, apps, and servers. Secrets. So, I\'m'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'talking about API keys, database credentials, tokens, files. So, all the stuff we are fiddling around when managing containers. And at first it usually feels manageable, but once you'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'start adding CI/CD or add more environments, maybe more hosts, those same secrets can end up in multiple places like compost files, envy files, GitHub actions, CI/CD variables, and a'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'few other places where they definitely should not belong. And this is where Infysical, the sponsor of today\'s video, comes in because Infysical is an open-source platform for managing secrets, certificates, and privileged'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'access. And it gives you a central place to manage all your application and deployment secrets across all your different environments. The cool thing about Infysical is that it integrates with many of the platforms and tools you'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'probably already use. For example, it has a docker and docker compos workflow where your containers can fetch secrets through in physical CLI using a secure machine identity. So instead of baking'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'secrets into images or hard- coding them in config files or compost or adding files everywhere, you can just manage them centrally and inject them when the container starts. And the same is also'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
